Non-Custodial: Gives the user control over the private key. The private key will usually be provided in the form of 12 or 24 words the wallet will give you. So long as you have those words somewhere safe, you can access your #bitcoin by typing them into pretty much any wallet.
It's good to think of custodial #Bitcoin wallets like banks who can freeze your funds, withhold them, or lose them in a hack.

Custodial: Someone else holds your private key. Any cryptocurrency exchange that holds #Bitcoin for you like @Binance or @Coinbase is an example of a custodial wallet. This means that they have control over your Bitcoin, not you.

1/6 Every #Bitcoin wallet comes with a private key allowing you to spend your bitcoin. How you store it is one of the things that makes Bitcoin unlike anything else. You have two choices when it comes to how a wallet will produce a private key, custodial and noncustodial
